  <h1>Harmful Language: Definitions & Categories</h1>

    <p>
        Harmful language refers to any expression that causes psychological, emotional, 
        social, or physical harm to individuals or groups. It can include insults, threats, 
        discrimination, or any form of degrading communication. Categorising harmful 
        language helps in moderation, analysis, and developing safer online environments.
    </p>

    <!-- Category Sections -->

    <div class="category">
        <h2>1. Abusive / Insulting Language</h2>
        <p>Language intended to belittle or demean an individual, without targeting protected characteristics.</p>

        <div class="example-box">
            Example: “You’re so useless; nobody wants you on this team.”
        </div>

        <p><strong>Key Features:</strong> Personal insults, name-calling, belittling, not identity-related.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="category">
        <h2>2. Hate Speech (Targeting Protected Characteristics)</h2>
        <p>
            Hostile or derogatory language directed at individuals because of protected traits 
            such as race, ethnicity, religion, gender, disability, sexual orientation, etc.
        </p>

        <div class="example-box">
            Example: “People from that ethnic group are not welcome here.”
        </div>

        <p><strong>Key Features:</strong> Identity-based attack, generalisations, exclusion, discrimination.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="category">
        <h2>3. Dehumanisation</h2>
        <p>
            Language that describes a person or group as less than human, comparing them to animals, 
            objects, or sub-human beings.
        </p>

        <div class="example-box">
            Example: “They’re like animals; they don’t deserve rights.”
        </div>

        <p><strong>Key Features:</strong> Removal of dignity, comparisons to animals/objects, justification for harm.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="category">
        <h2>4. Threats / Harassment</h2>
        <p>
            Language expressing intent to cause harm or ongoing intimidation, including physical threats 
            or repeated harassment.
        </p>

        <div class="example-box">
            Example: “I'm going to come after you if you post that again.”
        </div>

        <p><strong>Key Features:</strong> Threatening harm, intimidation, repeated targeting.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="category">
        <h2>5. Toxic Aggression</h2>
        <p>
            Highly hostile or aggressive language meant to provoke or escalate conflict, not necessarily 
            tied to identity or explicit threats.
        </p>

        <div class="example-box">
            Example: “You’re pathetic—just get lost already!”
        </div>

        <p><strong>Key Features:</strong> Aggressive tone, hostility, escalation of conflict.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="category">
        <h2>6. Neutral / Non-harmful</h2>
        <p>
            Language that is safe, respectful, factual, or otherwise non-aggressive. Includes polite disagreement.
        </p>

        <div class="example-box">
            Example: “I don’t agree with your opinion, but I see your point.”
        </div>

        <p><strong>Key Features:</strong> No insults, no hostility, respectful communication.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="category">
        <h2>7. Ambiguous</h2>
        <p>
            Language where the meaning or intent is unclear and depends on context.
        </p>

        <div class="example-box">
            Example: “Watch yourself next time.”
        </div>

        <p><strong>Key Features:</strong> Multiple interpretations possible, unclear tone or intention.</p>
    </div>

